            <td>1990</td>
            <td>7.4</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2000</td>
            <td>8.9</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2010</td>
            <td>10.6</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2020</td>
            <td>12.0</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>There are many devices on the market for conserving water: composting toilets, pedal faucets, systems to re-use &lsquo;grey&rsquo; water from sinks and baths to flush the toilets, water-saving sprinklers. And there are a number of other approaches to saving water: leakage control, metering, pricing, effluent charges, as well as public education, ordinances and code modifications.</p>

<p>The area served by OWASA would need <em>substantially</em> less water if even moderate conservation measures were followed; the above data is only the tip of the iceberg. Some people have reacted to the conservation argument by saying: &ldquo;Great, let&rsquo;s build the biggest reservoir we need at University Lake <em>and</em> Cane Creek and guarantee an adequate water supply for the longest time possible.&rdquo; Cane Creek residents have typically responded by saying: &ldquo;Great, why don&rsquo;t you build a 10 mgd facility at University Lake that will give you an adequate water supply up to the target year of 2006 and don&rsquo;t bother us.&rdquo; If water conservaton is taken seriously, one option is to build a smaller reservoir at Cane Creek, which will substantially reduce the amount of land needed, or go ahead with a 10 mgd facility and University Lake instead of the contemplated 13 mgd reservoir.</p>

<p>There was reasonable interest in the talk I gave recently on water conservation to the Orange County Task Force. But most public officials felt there was little they could do, since their hands are tied by building and plumbing codes (which they also feel helpless to change). It&rsquo;s ironic that codes which were originally established to protect the public now make it impossible, in most parts of the country, to conserve water. If public officials around the country viewed themselves more as advocates than bureaucrats, our codes might be made to work for us instead of against us. OWASA, like most public utilities, views its role as simply responding to &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo; public demands. This was feasible, although shortsighted, when energy was cheap and abundant; it is certainly not feasible now.</p>

<p>If local government and utilities viewed their role as advocates, they could research water-saving devices and systems and then present this information to contractors and developers. Many of these systems are no more expensive than conventional ones; any small added expense could be offset by the increased publicity and public goodwill for the developer.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Whatever reservoir site is finally used, Orange County, like many counties across the United States, will be faced with severe water shortages sooner or later; even if strict water conservation is practiced, as long as population continues to increase there is going to be a time when there will be severe water shortages. The problem is with us; the best we can do is respond to it creatively. Water conservation, along with proper watershed planning and management, are the most creative alternatives available now. How we respond will determine the quality of life ahead of us.</p>
														</div>


				
